The Diseases of Globalization
Globalization is put to the toughest test ever before.
Tensions simmer everywhere.
The majority of sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling with economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk a new recession.
War is now threatening in Iraq.
For proponents of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its advantages apparently concentrated in a few places ?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented ?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they barely suffice.
Certain regions of the world have gained significant benefits from globalization, particularly East Asia and China over the past few years.
Some regions, however, have withdrawn from meager benefits, particularly Black Africa.
The American government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they are battling.
African leaders, affirm the US leaders, claim that Africa's slow growth is due to the inaptitude of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Let's consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced levels of living that have decreased over the past two decades, while a large number of Asian countries that ranked among the lowest in international comparisons of government in each country (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with large populations and therefore large domestic markets tend to grow more quickly than countries with small populations.
(As with all this kind of economic trends, there are counterexamples.)
Coastal countries tend to be more performant than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Countries in the process of development that border rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to be more performing than countries that are far from major markets.
These differences hold great importance.
If the rich countries do not care much about these structural problems, the chasms between winners and losers will continue to widen.
If wealthy countries blame unfortunate countries for claiming they are culturally or politically unfit to benefit from globalisation, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify unrest.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to move to a more serious approach to globalization than is offered by the rich countries, and particularly America.
This approach must start with the most urgent task, namely responding to the basic needs of the world's poorest people.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated primarily due to better governance within their country.
But in others, an honest look at the evidence gathered will reveal that the main causes of poverty concern diseases, climate instability, poor soils, market distances, etc.
An honest evaluation would further indicate that the poorest countries are unable to gather sufficient funds to tackle such problems on their own.
Rather than seeing wealthy countries give more lectures on the poor governance of poor countries, real solutions require wealthy countries to provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
A striking case will illustrate this situation.
Controlling diseases requires a healthcare system capable of providing life-saving medicines and basic preventive services, such as bed nets to combat malaria and vitamins to combat nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least around $40 per person and per year.
This amount represents only a grain of sand for rich countries that systematically spend more than $2,000 per person per year on health, but it exceeds the reach of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of $200 per person.
A functioning healthcare system would cost more than the entire government's revenue !
Even though Malawi is well governed, its population will die in large numbers from the effects of diseases until it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires us to think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Rather than scolding the poor for their "sins", we must offer cautious diagnoses, as a good doctor would, for each country and each region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that slow their economic growth and development.
In certain regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly stems from geographical isolation.
Over there, the task involves building roads, aerial connections and internet connectivity to help these remote regions create productive links with the world.
Rich countries must contribute to the funding of these projects.
In Black Africa, the main challenges focus on controlling diseases, soil fertility, and educational opportunity development.
Foreign assistance is once again required.
In other regions, the main problems concern a lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the complexities inherent in globalization seriously.
The one-size-fits-all ideology of the Washington consensus is outdated.
On the eve of war, it is urgent to tackle the tough task of making everyone benefit from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinders of the wealthy and if we mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
